{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17621798","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17621798"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:58:12+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:58:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16774"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16774","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16774"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.79,0.03,0.1,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9465"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66893"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9465","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9465"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16774"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52347"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5065"},{"type":"tags","id":"5067"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22364"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22368"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66893","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/66893"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThiazide diuretics are commonly prescribed antihypertensive medications that act on the renal tubules to modify ion transport.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary mechanism of action of thiazide diuretics?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Inhibits epithelial sodium channels in collecting duct","Blocks sodium-chloride cotransporter in distal convoluted tubule","Antagonises aldosterone receptors in collecting duct","Inhibits sodium-potassium-chloride cotransporter in loop of Henle","Blocks carbonic anhydrase in proximal tubule"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThiazide diuretics work by \u003Cstrong\u003Eblocking the sodium-chloride cotransporter in the distal convoluted tubule\u003C/strong\u003E. This reduces sodium and chloride reabsorption, leading to increased urinary excretion of these ions along with water. This mechanism produces their therapeutic effects of reducing blood pressure and extracellular fluid volume.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibition of epithelial sodium channels in the collecting duct\u003C/strong\u003E is the mechanism of potassium-sparing diuretics like amiloride.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAntagonism of aldosterone receptors in the collecting duct\u003C/strong\u003E is how spironolactone works.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibition of the sodium-potassium-chloride cotransporter in the loop of Henle\u003C/strong\u003E is the mechanism of loop diuretics such as furosemide.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlocking carbonic anhydrase in the proximal tubule\u003C/strong\u003E describes the action of carbonic anhydrase inhibitors like acetazolamide.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThiazide diuretics also have the unique effect of promoting calcium reabsorption, making them useful in treating calcium-containing kidney stones and osteoporosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Thiazide diuretics inhibit sodium-chloride cotransporter in the distal convoluted tubule, leading to increased sodium and chloride excretion.","The therapeutic effects of thiazides include reduced blood pressure and extracellular fluid volume.","Unlike other diuretics, thiazides promote calcium reabsorption while increasing sodium excretion."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52347"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16774"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52347","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/52347"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-03T07:45:41+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-03T07:46:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9465"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66893"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"i